  "text": "Within the meta-analysis literature, the recognition of heterogeneity has led to the development of procedures for random effects meta-analyses [CITATION_1] . However, the implications of heterogeneity, outside of the methodological literature on how to conduct meta-analyses, have not been fully explored. The goal of this article is to examine the implications of effect size heterogeneity for power analysis, the precision of effect estimation, and the planning of both original and replication research. Some of these implications are more easily dealt with than are others. We do not have definitive answers for every issue that we raise. Our ultimate goal is to begin an informed discussion of the problems posed by heterogeneity, rather than simply acting as if it does not exist.",
